  "prompt": "How do you write a six line poem?",
  "response": "Here's a guide to writing a six-line poem:\n\n1. Choose a theme or subject\n2. Decide on a poetic form or structure:\n- You could use a specific rhyme scheme (like ABABCC)\n- Write in free verse with no strict rhyming pattern\n- Use a consistent meter or syllable count\n\n3. Basic steps:\n- Start with a strong opening line\n- Develop your idea or imagery\n- Create a sense of progression\n- End with a meaningful conclusion\n\n4. Example styles:\n- Rhyming: \nBeneath the stars, a whisper calls\nWhere moonlight dances on the walls\nA gentle breeze, a soft refrain\nThat echoes like a sweet, soft strain\nThe night unfolds its dark embrace\nWith quiet, soft, and tender grace\n\n- Free verse:\nShadows lengthen across the field\nMemories drift like scattered leaves\nSilence speaks in muted tones\nFragments of forgotten dreams\nWeaving through the twilight\nEchoes of what once was\n\n5. Tips:\n- Use vivid imagery\n- Choose precise words\n- Create an emotional connection\n- Read your poem aloud to check flow\n\nRemember, poetry is creative, so there's no single \"correct\" way to write a six-line poem.",
